The main concern during prosthodontic surgery for a favorable prosthetic outcome lies primarily in ensuring proper occlusion because it directly influences both mechanical stability of restorations and successful integration of dental implants through optimal force transmission. Properly balanced occlusions reduce excessive loading risks while promoting long-term functional durability and patient satisfaction.

\boxed{A}

The summary focuses only on clinically significant factors related to surgical planning and treatment efficacy—specifically emphasizing how accurate occlusion supports not only restoration function but also enhances osseointegration via controlled mastication loads. These findings align closely with established principles where predictable biological responses depend heavily upon precise occlusal design throughout all phases of rehabilitation.

